Taking the free pawn doesn't remove the queen's defense of e4. 11. ... Qe7? may have been a bit of a blunder, since black didn't have to give away the pawn. However, it was a doubled and isolated pawn and it was doomed to a short lifespan either way.

Not the usual follow up. I frequently follow g5 with Nh4 and trade my knight for black's bishop, doing damage to the king's castle in the process. This time, the black knight looks more vulnerable. Probably the safe move here is 18. ... Nd7.

Oops. Black walked into a blunder here, and white jumps at the chance to add to his material lead by winning the exchange. Funny thing is, I almost was afraid to play 23. Nc6. It felt like a trap. Why would black give this away if he didn't have something sneaky planned in response? I looked and looked, but found no traps, so finally went for it and got an immediate resignation from my opponent.
